  <h2>New Brunswick Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    New Brunswick’s growing season is shaped by maritime influence, variable spring warming,
    and meaningful early fall frost risk outside coastal pockets. While the province doesn’t
    experience the intense prairie heat of western Canada, steady summer accumulation can still
    produce strong crops when timing is realistic.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Spring can feel slow and uneven</h3>
  <p>
    Snow may melt early, but soil temperatures often lag. Cool, damp springs are common,
    especially in northern and inland areas. Planting warm-season crops too early can delay
    growth more than it helps.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re unsure whether soil or air temperature matters more, this guide explains
    <a href="/guides/best-soil-thermometer-for-gardening-in-cold-climates/">
      why soil temperature is critical in cold climates
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Maritime influence moderates extremes</h3>
  <p>
    Coastal areas often avoid the most severe heat and cold swings, resulting in a steadier —
    but sometimes slower — growing season. Interior regions tend to accumulate more heat
    in mid-summer but also carry greater frost risk.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Late summer cooling matters</h3>
  <p>
    By late August, overnight lows begin trending downward across much of the province.
    Warm-season crops like tomatoes, peppers, and squash slow quickly once nights cool,
    even if daytime temperatures remain comfortable.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you garden in a shorter season, this overview of
    <a href="/guides/what-is-considered-a-short-growing-season/">
      what defines a short growing season
    </a>
    can help frame expectations.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Local topography creates microclimates</h3>
  <p>
    River valleys, forest edges, and slight elevation changes can shift frost timing by days
    or even weeks. Low-lying inland sites frequently frost earlier than exposed coastal slopes.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your yard behaves differently than the regional average,
    <a href="/guides/how-microclimates-change-frost-dates/">
      this explains how microclimates alter frost timing
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Check frost timing and remaining seasonal heat for your nearest station.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity to realistic heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Add margin if you’re inland, elevated, or in a known frost pocket.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In New Brunswick, steady planning and realistic variety choice matter more than pushing early planting dates.
  </p>
</section>